          "title": "Agrippa's tragic *en oligo*",
          "body": "The chapter ends not in triumph but in pathos. Agrippa, who knows the Prophets, who has just heard the gospel from its clearest exponent, deflects with one sardonic phrase: *en oligo me peitheis Christianon poiesai* — *in a short time you would persuade me to become a Christian* (v. 28). The grammar can be read as mocking (*you think you can make me a Christian that easily?*) or wistful (*almost you persuade me*). Either way the result is the same: Agrippa rises (v. 30), walks out, and is never heard from again in Scripture. Paul's reply (v. 29) is one of the great pastoral utterances in Acts: he wishes that all who hear him this day might become as he is — except for the chains. The free man stands chained; the king walks out enslaved. The chapter ends with the most poignant tragedy in Luke's second volume: a man who heard the gospel from Paul himself and chose not to believe."
